BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:JFRLict2kT-TWbmz6UuKe
SUMMARY:UW Psychology Distinguished Alumni Lecture\, Feat. Dr. Cynthia Berg
DTSTAMP:20260316T010604Z
DTSTART:20260318T223000Z
DESCRIPTION:University of Washington Department of Psychology - Distinguish
	ed Alumni Lecture\, Feat. Dr. Cynthia Berg\n\nA Self- and Social-Regulatio
	n Perspective on Type 1 Diabetes Management Across the Life Span\n\nType 1
	 diabetes is a difficult illness to manage and requires daily self-regulat
	ion \\(e.g.\, planning to meet diabetes goals\, self-efficacy\, and managi
	ng emotions\\) as well as social regulation \\(disclosing to others to obt
	ain needed assistance\\). Although aspects of parent involvement in diabet
	es management decline across adolescence and into young adulthood\, our lo
	ngitudinal studies show that having family members and romantic partners w
	ho are knowledgeable about one’s diabetes behaviors and are available to h
	elp when needed is associated with better diabetes outcomes. Social regula
	tion can also facilitate more effective use of technologies such as contin
	uous glucose monitors by sharing GM data with others. These studies have s
	erved as the foundation for randomized clinical trials that hold promise f
	or optimizing self- and social-regulation on a daily basis for individuals
	 across the life span.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/uw
	-psychology-distinguished-alumni-lecture-feat-dr-cynthia-berg/18314196/202
	6-03-18T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/uw-psychology-distinguish
	ed-alumni-lecture-feat-dr-cynthia-berg/18314196/2026-03-18T00
LOCATION:UW Hans Rosling Center for Population Health\, 3980 15th Ave NE\, 
	Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
